Now let me clean up unused imports. The `inputRef`, `ChangeEvent`, and the useEffect for focus are no longer needed since SmoothInput handles its own focus. Actually, let me check if the useEffect is still useful. It was:

```useEffect(() => {
 if (isEditing && inputRef.current) {
      requestAnimationFrame(() => {
        inputRef.current?.focus();
        inputRef.current?.select();
      });
    }
  }, [isEditing]);
```

This is no longer needed because:
1. `inputRef` is no longer used
2. SmoothInput manages its own focus (it doesn't auto-focus, but the user will click the edit button and then the SmoothInput appears - the browser may or may not focus it)


Actually, I need to reconsider - when the edit button is clicked, focus shifts to the button itself, so when SmoothInput mounts it won't automatically receive focus. The useEffect was handling this by explicitly focusing the input after it appeared, but now that it's gone, the user would need to click into the SmoothInput manually to start typing. I should restore some focus logic to maintain the original behavior.

I can use a ref callback to capture the input element when SmoothInput mounts, then use an effect to focus and select the text once it's available. This way I'm working with SmoothInput's internal input element rather than trying to manage focus from outside.

Setting up the ref callback... I need to be careful about how the ref callback interacts with SmoothInput's internal ref management. Since SmoothInput uses its own `inputRef` internally, my callback ref should work fine on the DOM element itself. I'll add a separate effect to handle the focus and selection when editing starts, using a regular ref instead of a callback to avoid complications with the dependency array.

